Coming of Age Under Trump: Online Appendix

Author

Nikolaos Vichos

Introduction

This document is the online appendix for the paper âComing of Age Under Trump The Effect of First Electoral Exposure in a Trump Election on Long-Term Support for Liberal Democratic Protections of Media Freedom.â Here I have included additional methodological details not included in the main body of the paper.

Regression Design

In my analysis, I estimated a series of sharp RD models using local polynomial regression. Each model used local linear estimation (polynomial order = 1) and MSE-optimal bandwidth selection to obtain the treatment effect at the cutoff.

Index Construction

Internal Consistency

To evaluate the internal consistency of the items used in the indices, I computed Cronbachâs Î± for each the aforementioned set of items. Both the raw and the standardized alpha (Î± = 0.7) show acceptable consistency (Taber 2018).

Factor Structure

Next, I used principal axis factoring (no rotation) to assess whether the three items capture a single underlying construct. Based on the Kaiser criterion (eigenvalue > 1) a single factor was retained for each item. Factor loadings for each indexâs selected items were above 0.6, confirming unidimensionality.

Index Rescaling

Each index is constructed by extracting individual scores on the first factor and rescaling them to range from 0 to 1 using minâmax normalization. Even though higher values indicate higher support for liberal democratic, this was reversed during production of the coefficient plot for visualization and interpretability purposes, due to the specific design of the rdrobust package (Calonico, Cattaneo, and Farrell 2025). In the package, the threshold is âcrossedâ from left to rightâhence, normally, a positive effect would suggest more positive media attitudes among those who voted for the first time in 2012. However, for clearer comprehension, the results have been reversed, and the indices can be interpreted in accordance with the wording of the hypotheses. For details on the process of index construction, refer to the replication code file.

Robustness Checks

I present the robustness checks conducted for the two models (Simple vs Controls) and for the three different RD estimates (Conventional, Bias-Adjusted, Bias-Adjusted with Robust SEs). I test the resultsâ robustness to different bandwidths, placebo cut-offs (different ages), and different polynomial degrees.

To narrow them down and improve readability, I only include subgroups that had statistically significant results (i.e., independents and Republicans). Overall, the sensitivity of the results to the first and third specifications, as well as to the addition of robust standard errors casts some doubt on their statistical significance.
